Load the Data

For this homework, we will use the shark attack data to visualize where the attacks occurred. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

sharks <- read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv") %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  filter(longitude !="NA" & latitude !="NA") %>% # pulling out NA locations
  mutate(longitude = as.numeric(longitude)) # converting longitude to numeric
  1. Use the range of the latitude and longitude to build an appropriate bounding box for your map.
sharks %>% 
  select(longitude, latitude) %>% 
  summary()
##    longitude         latitude    
##  Min.   :-124.7   Min.   :32.59  
##  1st Qu.:-123.1   1st Qu.:34.04  
##  Median :-122.0   Median :36.70  
##  Mean   :-121.4   Mean   :36.36  
##  3rd Qu.:-119.6   3rd Qu.:38.18  
##  Max.   :-117.1   Max.   :41.56
long <- c(-124.7, -117.1)
lat  <- c(32.59, 41.56)
bbox <- make_bbox(long, lat, f=0.07)
  1. Load a map from stamen in a terrain style projection and display the map.
shark_map <- get_stadiamap(bbox, maptype = "stamen_terrain", zoom=7)
##   Stadia Maps  Stamen Design  OpenMapTiles  OpenStreetMap contributors.
  1. Build a map that overlays the recorded observations of shark attacks in California.
ggmap(shark_map)+
  geom_point(data=sharks, aes(longitude, latitude), size=0.70, color="red", alpha=0.8) +
  labs(x="Longitude",
       y="Latitude",
       title = "Recorded Shark Attacks in CA")

  1. Build a map that only shows the fatalities.
ggmap(shark_map)+
  geom_point(data=sharks %>% filter(injury=="fatal"), aes(longitude, latitude), size=0.70, color="red", alpha=0.8)

  1. Build the same map (fatalities only), but this time make it interactive using leaflet. Also, color the points red.
sharks %>% 
  summarize(
  lon_min=min(longitude, na.rm=T),
  lon_max=max(longitude, na.rm=T),
  lat_min=min(latitude, na.rm=T),
  lat_max=max(latitude, na.rm=T)
  )
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   lon_min lon_max lat_min lat_max
##     <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1   -125.   -117.    32.6    41.6
lon_min <- -124.7267    
lon_max <- -117.1467    
lat_min <- 32.58833 
lat_max <- 41.56167 
leaflet(sharks %>%filter(injury=="fatal")) %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stadia.StamenTerrain) %>% 
  addCircleMarkers(
    lng = ~longitude, 
    lat = ~latitude,
    radius = 2,
    stroke = FALSE,
    fillOpacity = 0.7,
    color="red"
  ) %>% 
  addScaleBar(position = "bottomleft") %>% 
  fitBounds(lng1=lon_min, lat1=lat_min,
            lng2 = lon_max,lat2 = lat_max)
  1. Which county has the highest number of recorded shark attacks? Make a map that only shows the attacks in this county. (hint: it may help improve the map if you remove duplicate locations, i.e.multiple attacks at the same location.)
sharks %>% 
 count(county) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))
## # A tibble: 21  2

#San Diego County has the highest number of recorded shark attacks
ggmap(shark_map)+
  geom_point(data=sharks %>% filter(county=="San Diego") %>% distinct(location, .keep_all = TRUE ), aes(longitude, latitude), size=0.70, color="red", alpha=0.8)
